REVERSE ENGINEERING STATEMENT
================================================================================

This software was developed through lawful interoperability reverse engineering
of the PrivadoVPN Android application (com.privado.android). No proprietary
source code, object code, or compiled binaries from Privado Networks AG were
copied, incorporated, or distributed as part of this project.

The following information was obtained through legitimate observation methods:

  1. API ENDPOINTS — Discovered via network traffic analysis (HTTPS inspection
     of the official app's outbound requests using user-controlled proxy on
     user-owned device). These are functional interface specifications, not
     copyrightable expression.

  2. AUTHENTICATION FLOW — Observed via the same network traffic analysis.
     Standard OAuth 2.0 / token-based authentication. The flow itself is not
     protectable; only a specific creative implementation would be.

  3. API KEY (9f994c466340e8f2ed60a99396fecb6a) — This key is embedded in
     plain text within the publicly distributed Android APK file. It is
     identical for ALL users and ALL installations. It is not a personal
     credential, not a trade secret (publicly distributed in cleartext), and
     not access-restricted. It functions as an application identifier, not a
     security boundary. Extractable by anyone via: `apktool d privado.apk &&
     grep -r "api_key" res/ smali/`.

  4. SERVER HOSTNAMES — Returned by the public API in response to authenticated
     requests from a paying subscriber. Using one's own subscription credentials
     to query available servers is normal authorized use.

  5. PROTOCOL PARAMETERS — IKEv2/IPsec, WireGuard, and OpenVPN are open
     standards. The specific parameters (cipher suites, key exchange methods,
     DH groups) were observed from connection configuration responses. These
     are functional specifications, not copyrightable expression.

